The built-in types — a quick map.

The types you will meet in the first hour, organized by mutability and shape.

Numeric types — int, float, complex, and bool. All immutable. Int literals can be decimal, binary with zero-b prefix, octal with zero-o, or hex with zero-x. Float literals like three point one four. Complex literals like three plus four j. Bool literals true and false.

Text and binary types. String is immutable, written with single or double quotes, or as an f-string with f-quote. Bytes is immutable, written with b-quote. Bytearray is mutable, constructed from bytes.

None — the no-value singleton. Its type is none-type.

Sequence types — list, mutable, square brackets. Tuple, immutable, parentheses or just comma-separated. Range, immutable, range of n.

Mapping type — dict, mutable, braces with key colon value.

Set types — set, mutable, braces with just values. Frozenset, immutable.

Notebook four covers the collection types properly. This notebook focuses on the scalar atomic types.
